SIMPLE: spatter
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spatter
<hw>Spat"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Spattered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Spattering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From the root of
<ets>spit</ets> salvia.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To sprinkle with a
liquid or with any wet substance, as water, mud, or the like; to make
wet of foul spots upon by sprinkling; <as>as, to <ex>spatter</ex> a
coat; to <ex>spatter</ex> the floor; to <ex>spatter</ex> boots with
mud</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Upon any occasion he is to be <qex>spattered</qex> over with the
blood of his people.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To distribute by sprinkling; to sprinkle around;
<as>as, to <ex>spatter</ex> blood</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Fig.: To injure by aspersion; to defame; to soil;
also, to throw out in a defamatory manner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spatter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spatter
<hw>Spat"ter</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To throw something out of the
mouth in a scattering manner; to sputter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That mind must needs be irrecoverably depraved, which, . . .
tasting but once of one just deed, <qex>spatters</qex> at it, and abhors
the relish ever after.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spatterdashed</ent>⟦br⟧
